How do _you_ measure success? And how does your organization do it? For most, success is that yardstick that people outside the company wave around, hoping to make sense of your efforts. It’s been almost thirty years since the Balanced Scorecard concept made its debut in _Harvard Business Review_. Now, you might not be a fan of the quadrants they propose, but almost every scorecard has a trusty old [[The Power of the 2 x 2 Matrix|two by two matrix]]. And any organization in need of a stealthy enterprise architect probably already has a set of measures—even if they’re not front and centre as a proper scorecard.

Capturing what motivates an organization, whether it’s through OKRs (Objectives and Key Results) or KPIs (Key Performance Indicators), is a bit of an art form. In the spirit of Mark Twain, “There are lies, damn lies, and statistics.” True enough! But, if the leadership is taking those numbers seriously, for better or worse, they’re going to _manage_ them.

For a Stealth Enterprise Architect, using ArchiMate to piece together the logic of a scorecard is like solving a puzzle. You’re mapping out the dependencies between the drivers, goals, and measurable outcomes. Not only does this give you insight into the big picture, but it might also come in handy for other Stealth EA deliverables—or for a cheeky little review of the scorecard itself.

One of the most concrete ways that scorecards help the Stealth EA is when you bring value streams into the mix as part of your [[Business Capability Planning]] toolkit. Goals and measures are the lifeblood of value streams. When people set out to change outcomes and hit their targets, they often do so by optimizing or creating new value streams. And being able to connect the dots between the business capabilities that need some extra TLC is key to helping the organization achieve its version of success.

So, how do _you_ measure up? If you’re not keeping an eye on the measures driving your organization’s strategic plan, how will you know if all your hard work (and everyone else’s) is leading to success?

